Observation Details: Continuing bird originally found yesterday (9/5), by L. Corneliussen and Cochranes. We had been at the feeders for almost 50 minutes since the bird was last seen by others, when I heard "chimp" calls from the butterfly bush just to the east of the feeders. Shortly thereafter, the bird came to the main feeder in the middle of the yard and fed with ANHUs a total of four separate times over the next 11 minutes, always announcing its presence by calling. First appearing at 8:53 am and and not seen after it fed last, at 9:04 am. Bob and I departed shortly thereafter.  Clearly a female-plumaged Archilochus hummingbird -  Primaries: Photos show strong sharp taper to P6, often times being described as appearing “cut off.” Other primaries narrower than BCHU. Specifically, P4 and P5 are somewhat tapered and not rounded as would be expected of female-plumaged BCHU. Hint of notch on inner web of inner primaries can be seen in photo ML260623411, which supports RTHU. Narrowing outer web of P10 also supports RTHU and can be seen in photos ML260623221, ML260684201, and ML260623281 when zoomed way in.  Other field notes: Dusky auricular and white post-ocular spot. Bill is also shorter, straighter, and less decurved than female BCHU. One thing that was notable for this bird in the field was it seemed more contrasting (deep green above, darker wings, brighter white below, golden green on crown), versus overall duskiness of BCHU. Tail noticeably longer past tips of primaries, but this is not necessarily diagnostic. Behavior: At one point it was facing me and hovering in flight with tail feathers flared while facing off with an ANHU. I watched the bird more and noted that as it flew it did not engage in tail pumping/flicking behavior often attributed to BCHU in flight. Wish I got a photo/video of that, but just as I turned my camera to video settings the bird took off. 4th MRN Co. record and the first one away from the feeders at K. Hansen's Gallery (per eBird), as others have noted.   *CBRC Accepted Record #2020-085  Literature consulted: https://birdersjournal.ca/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/hummingbird-id.pdf

Media notes: Taking a break in Serviceberry between Penstemon visits.
Observation Details: Male and female. With all the on and off showers this morning, male making frequent visits to feed on Penstemon. Often times on rainy days, with the Penstemon nectar being more abundant, ( my guess) I will often see them take more breaks. I'm guessing this is the same male from last year, as he will take breaks in the closest Serviceberry. Last year he would also take breaks on the metal plant cage, but the cage is no longer there. Female taking significantly less trips, but would spend more time in the Penstemon. Perhaps just a quick meal before heading back to sit on nest. I don't get much time to observe the females this time of year due to them being beyond busy with nesting and raising young. I usually get much more time with them after nesting season, as most of the males are gone ( At least from the areas I observe them).

Continuing bird originally found yesterday (9/5), by L. Corneliussen and Cochranes. We had been at the feeders for almost 50 minutes since the bird was last seen by others, when I heard "chimp" calls from the butterfly bush just to the east of the feeders. Shortly thereafter, the bird came to the main feeder in the middle of the yard and fed with ANHUs a total of four separate times over the next 11 minutes, always announcing its presence by calling. First appearing at 8:53 am and and not seen after it fed last, at 9:04 am. Bob and I departed shortly thereafter.  Clearly a female-plumaged Archilochus hummingbird -  Primaries: Photos show strong sharp taper to P6, often times being described as appearing “cut off.” Other primaries narrower than BCHU. Specifically, P4 and P5 are somewhat tapered and not rounded as would be expected of female-plumaged BCHU. Hint of notch on inner web of inner primaries can be seen in photo ML260623411, which supports RTHU. Narrowing outer web of P10 also supports RTHU and can be seen in photos ML260623221, ML260684201, and ML260623281 when zoomed way in.  Other field notes: Dusky auricular and white post-ocular spot. Bill is also shorter, straighter, and less decurved than female BCHU. One thing that was notable for this bird in the field was it seemed more contrasting (deep green above, darker wings, brighter white below, golden green on crown), versus overall duskiness of BCHU. Tail noticeably longer past tips of primaries, but this is not necessarily diagnostic. Behavior: At one point it was facing me and hovering in flight with tail feathers flared while facing off with an ANHU. I watched the bird more and noted that as it flew it did not engage in tail pumping/flicking behavior often attributed to BCHU in flight. Wish I got a photo/video of that, but just as I turned my camera to video settings the bird took off. 4th MRN Co. record and the first one away from the feeders at K. Hansen's Gallery (per eBird), as others have noted.   *CBRC Accepted Record #2020-085  Literature consulted: https://birdersjournal.ca/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/hummingbird-id.pdf

Apparently first-year male based on the bill length and dark spotting in throat, even though it lacked extensive cinnamon/buff on feather edges.Photographs below are by Brad Hacker.  initally picked out from the many Anna's at the feeders by combination of whiter underparts, buff suffusion in the dusky green flanks, dark mask from bill to eye, and isolated white post ocular spot that that did not extend in pale line around ear coverts. These all indicated a Black-chinned (BCHU) or Ruby-throated (RTHU). I asked Brad to photograph the bird so we could check for potential Ruby-throated Hmmingbirds and distinguish how many different BCHUs were present, as this spcecies is considered rare locally after early September.  The photos showed the inner primaries were much narrower than outer primaries, confirming the bird as an Archilochus hummingbird. Of much greater interest, the photos showed that  the tip of  p10 was much narrower and more pointed that typically shown by BCHU and a feature consistent with RTHU. In addition, the bird was much brighter green above than the BCHUs seen, that day, another feature favoring RTHU.  Analysis of the photos and further field observations confirmed the identification as RTHU using the following criteria:  1.Narrow tip to p10 rather than blunt tip. 2. Notches on the inner primaries (e,g, p6), which are shown by RTHU but not BCHU. 3. In the tail, R4 was longer than R3, which again favors RTHU 4. The tips of the tail feathers were rounded, whereas BCHU tends to show a nipple shape to the ends of tail-feathers 5. The extension of the tail past the wing-tips was quite noticeable, which again favors RTHU. 6. The bill was straight and shorter compared to the longer, slightly decurved bills of the BCHU seen. 7. The bright green upperparts reaching all the way to the forehead is typical of RTHU, whereas most BCHUs, including those present, showed dull dirty green upperparts with the forecrown and forehead being grayish brown.

Observation Details: The broad outer primaries and narrow inner primaries (note change in width from P7 to P6) indicate an  Archilochus hummingbird. The relatively narrow and tapered P10, along with the notched inner webs of the inner primary tips are indicative of Ruby-throated Hummingbird.  This bird is an immature, as seen by the buff tips of the feathers, especially on the crown and nape.  The almost unmarked throat (with just a few metallic green feathers at the edge), as well as a tiny white tip to R2, point to the bird being a female. In addition, the inner primaries are mildly notched, not markedly so as would be the case for a male.

Continuing bird originally found yesterday (9/5), by L. Corneliussen and Cochranes. We had been at the feeders for almost 50 minutes since the bird was last seen by others, when I heard "chimp" calls from the butterfly bush just to the east of the feeders. Shortly thereafter, the bird came to the main feeder in the middle of the yard and fed with ANHUs a total of four separate times over the next 11 minutes, always announcing its presence by calling. First appearing at 8:53 am and and not seen after it fed last, at 9:04 am. Bob and I departed shortly thereafter.  Clearly a female-plumaged Archilochus hummingbird -  Primaries: Photos show strong sharp taper to P6, often times being described as appearing “cut off.” Other primaries narrower than BCHU. Specifically, P4 and P5 are somewhat tapered and not rounded as would be expected of female-plumaged BCHU. Hint of notch on inner web of inner primaries can be seen in photo ML260623411, which supports RTHU. Narrowing outer web of P10 also supports RTHU and can be seen in photos ML260623221, ML260684201, and ML260623281 when zoomed way in.  Other field notes: Dusky auricular and white post-ocular spot. Bill is also shorter, straighter, and less decurved than female BCHU. One thing that was notable for this bird in the field was it seemed more contrasting (deep green above, darker wings, brighter white below, golden green on crown), versus overall duskiness of BCHU. Tail noticeably longer past tips of primaries, but this is not necessarily diagnostic. Behavior: At one point it was facing me and hovering in flight with tail feathers flared while facing off with an ANHU. I watched the bird more and noted that as it flew it did not engage in tail pumping/flicking behavior often attributed to BCHU in flight. Wish I got a photo/video of that, but just as I turned my camera to video settings the bird took off. 4th MRN Co. record and the first one away from the feeders at K. Hansen's Gallery (per eBird), as others have noted.   *CBRC Accepted Record #2020-085  Literature consulted: https://birdersjournal.ca/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/hummingbird-id.pdf

Media notes: Feeding on Penstemon
Observation Details: Male and female. With all the on and off showers this morning, male making frequent visits to feed on Penstemon. Often times on rainy days, with the Penstemon nectar being more abundant, ( my guess) I will often see them take more breaks. I'm guessing this is the same male from last year, as he will take breaks in the closest Serviceberry. Last year he would also take breaks on the metal plant cage, but the cage is no longer there. Female taking significantly less trips, but would spend more time in the Penstemon. Perhaps just a quick meal before heading back to sit on nest. I don't get much time to observe the females this time of year due to them being beyond busy with nesting and raising young. I usually get much more time with them after nesting season, as most of the males are gone ( At least from the areas I observe them).

Locality: Southeast Farallon Island (Farallon Islands NWR, restricted access)
Observation Details: While I was conducting an area search mid-morning of the 29th, I happened to pass by the PRBO House and noticed Oscar staring intently at something in a Lavatera.  When I asked him what was up, he replied that he was trying to get a decent look at a small, non-Rufous Hummingbird.  I paused my area search, and we soon saw the bird feed briefly on the purple flowers.  Oscar quickly exclaimed “I think that might be a Ruby-throat!” but I was unsure.  My views had been brief and incomplete, and I thought that the throat looked too gray.  However, we radioed Jim to come out with the cameras (it being a slow, windy day I wasn’t carrying mine), which he did.  Since the bird had zoomed off, I decided it’d be best for me to quickly finish the area search while the other two looked for the hummingbird. 	When I returned, Oscar had the bird pinned down near the Coast Guard Tree, and was blazing away at it with my camera.  I studied it for about a minute through my binoculars, and was able to convince myself that it was, indeed, a Ruby-throated Hummingbird, a conclusion Oscar and Jim had already reached for themselves.  The next half hour or so was spent looking at the bird, trying to get photos (it was an elusive, quick-moving little bugger), and opening nets.  Eventually, I found the bird trapped in the Coast Guard net, and after extracting it, I took it in to the banding lab. 	Jim, Oscar and Jessie joined me there, and with their help, measured and photographed the bird.  Since we do not have a permit or the equipment to band hummingbirds, we released the bird unmarked after we had taken all the necessary biometric data and a series of photographs.  It flew off, and we never saw it again.  Description.  This bird was a small hummingbird, bright green above, and light gray below, with a white throat. 	Head: This bird had a bright, emerald-green crown and nape, contrasting with the clean grayish-white throat and black lores and dark gray auriculars.  The bill was long, straight and dark.  The lores were black, and distinctly arrowhead-shaped, swelling towards the eye, with no white above.  The auriculars were dark ashy-gray.  There was a small white post-ocular spot behind the eye. The sides of the neck were grayish, which wrapped around through the fore collar, to about halfway around the neck.  The throat below the area that would fill in to become the gorget was also white. 	Body: The bird had a completely bright, emerald green back and rump, which did not contrast with the crown.  The underparts were pale grayish-white, with some buffy edging to the flank feathers.  The undertail coverts were white. 	Tail: The tail was short, mostly green, and distinctly notched, which made the tail forked when the bird sat.  The tips of the rectrices were white, while the subterminal portions were black.   	Wings: The wings were black and long, reaching to the tip of the tail when folded.  The inner primaries were short and narrow, contrasting with the broader outer primaries.  The last primary, P10, narrowed toward the tip, giving the feather a scimitar shape, which was quite unlike the broad tip to the same feather that Black-chinned Hummingbirds have. 	Measurements: A suite of measurements were taken while the bird was in our banding lab.  Since Oscar Johnson has included these in his report, I will not repeat them here.  Discussion.  The bright, emerald-green back, shape of both the inner and outer primaries, as well as the face pattern rule out all other genera of North American hummingbirds than Archilochus, while the combination of measurements taken in-hand, the shape of the bill, and the length and shape of the primaries and tail effectively rule out Black-chinned Hummingbird.

Observation Details: This may sound like a tall tale. And it should. Seen first 8/23 in same vicinity of continuing BCHU. So description is a comparison of those 2 nearly identical birds with mostly separate ranges.  Pictures tell most of the story and slight details distinguishing RTHU from BCHU include: Smaller and straighter bill. Slightly narrower tips of primaries, with wingtips ending well above split tail. Behavior reminiscent of rufous, protecting space around the feeder. I’ve passed photos onto birders way more skilled and experienced then myself and no objections, and general consensus.  Recording on merlin 8/24 ID’d bird as RTHU, which. is. Not definitive -but it’s something.

Locality: DeAnza Mobile Home Park (walk-in access only)
Observation Details: HY female based on throat pattern, rounded rects. Regular visitor to the honeysuckle (every 30 minutes or less), had many various views, mostly in flight. Noted all of the same characteristics Alex did on 9/7. I took hundreds of photos and after an initial review will add that the tip of p10 appears consistent with RTHU (expected, given other field marks) - it does not have the broad club shaped tip typical of BCHU and appears relatively narrow/pointed in comparison. The short straight bill (for Archilochus), the strong contrasting head pattern (green cap, blackish face, very pale mostly clean throat) was very different than the BCHUs present here and that have been at my home feeders the last couple weeks. The BCHUs I have seen lately with paler throats/underparts were females that lacked any hint of a dark “mask” that stands out on this bird. Tail pumping was usually not done at all as the bird fed, though it did it very mildly on some occasions, but it was never really noticeable.   Photo review shows R4 slightly longer than R3 (should be vice versa on BCHU). Outer of web of P10 is very narrow and tapers toward the tip - this would appear wider and grow noticeably broader near the tip in BCHU. Inner primary tips appear "cut off" rather than blunt/rounded  I believe this is right in the prime window for RTHU in the state.

It seems that with new sighting I am now learning the habits of the birds. It looks that the injured bill young male I photographed in the West sideyard patch has claimed that area as his, while the adult male is currently holding the backyard patch. I was so pleased to see an adult male!!  Generally, young males are around 90-95% of the hummer populous.... UNTIL winter has taken a step over the migrant period. Then the birds that remain are generally adult males with a few young males claiming territories - often temporarily- or becoming nomadic trespassers with occasional sightings. I like to believe that these adults could be returnees, as all young birds that would have been here previous years - along with past adults - would have had adult plumage after their first wintering season post hatching. This helps support that many of the adults may be returns this late in the year. Hummers are known for fidelity among sites and even behaviors, so experienced birds that overwinter in the US will generally continue to, even if it's not at the same locale; often time it is, and for years sometimes.

Adult male Ruby-throated Hummingbird found and photographed by Curtis A. Marantz on 10 November 2017 at Lake Tamarisk, Desert Center, Riverside County, California.
Observation Details: This was a notably small bird with a posture that was typical of a hummingbird.  The bill was long, slim, and tubular.  I further noted that the bill was very slightly decurved and just barely longer than the head was wide.  The forehead was sloping and the crown was gently rounded on a head that was unremarkable in size for a hummingbird.  The neck was short and inconspicuous, yet seemingly slimmer than that of an Anna’s Hummingbird.  I also thought this bird was a little slimmer and seemingly smaller than an Anna’s Hummingbird, but I never clearly saw the two species in direct comparison.  The wings were long and sickle-like with the primaries extending well beyond the secondaries in the closed wing and the wingtip having a stair-stepped appearance given the graduated primaries, but I failed to note both the primary projection and the placement of the wingtips relative to the tail.  I noted quite clearly that the tail was short and notched at the tip, with the corners tapering to relatively finely pointed tips, but I did not notice the length of the tail relative to field-marks on the body.  The undertail and uppertail coverts were both relatively long, yet both fell short of even the center of the tail.  The legs were short and the feet were quite small.  I really saw nothing on the spread wings of the flying bird that was all that useful apart from the fact that the wings were beating very rapidly, and that they were relatively long and slim. This was a colorful and well-marked bird.  I never clearly saw the forehead, but the crown, nape, and back and side of the neck were an iridescent, forest-green in color that was both relatively dark and seemingly with a blue component to the green.  The back, scapulars, and rump were also about this same shade of green, as apparently were the wing coverts located near the bird’s shoulder.  I thought the uppertail coverts were about the same color as the rump, but the central rectrices appeared to be slightly darker, albeit with at least some green iridescence.  The outer several pairs of rectrices appeared to be uniformly black from above, but it was also a bit difficult to see the spread tail clearly.  I was never quite sure about the color of the lores, the supraloral region, or the superciliary region, all of which appeared to be quite dark.  I did notice in the field, a small, white spot behind each eye and also that the lower part of the face, from the chin across the submoustachial region, were uniformly black in color.  The gorget often appeared black when seen in less than ideal light, and it was squared off at the corners without the flared “wings” that are typical of Anna’s and especially Costa’s Hummingbirds.  When the light hit the throat just right it glowed with a fire-red color that was both a bit different from the bright pink of the Anna’s Hummingbirds and with the red contrasting sharply with the black of the chin and upper part of the throat.  The lower edge of the gorget was sharply demarcated along a line that extended straight across the demarcation between the throat and upper breast, below which was a broad, and strikingly white collar that extended across the breast and sides.  The flanks were rather broadly about the same shade of forest-green as the upperparts, but the center of the lower breast and belly appeared to be narrowly whitish.  I further noted that the lower part of the belly and the undertail coverts had a somewhat dingy and diffusely mottled appearance, but the underside of the tail appeared to be uniformly dark. The bill was black, the eyes were dark enough as to appear black in the field, and what I could see of the legs and feet when the bird was hovering at the feeder appeared to be at least blackish if not truly black. My impression was that this bird was rather quiet, in that I heard it give only two or three times soft “tschew” calls that were similar to those of Black-chinned Hummingbird (A. alexandri).

Also seen 10/25 only twice on both days.  Small hummingbird, female bright rich green back and top of head with grayish wash in face. Underside bright white, including throat with faint dusky streaking, slightest of green wash on sides. Tail dark with obvious tip edged in black then white. No cinnamon tones seen. Bill moderate in length. The tail was never seen open and no vocalizations were heard. Separation from ruby-throated hummingbird was determined with help from individuals who live where both species occur. The deciding character were the shape of the inner primaries where this bird showed blunter tips than would be expected from a ruby-throated.

Originally seen this morn but unidentified by EM. For some non fathomable reason EM did not mention this and opted for the “there are migrants”. A truly miraculous find by RR to “relocate” this beauty and get the word out to EM. EM was at cross country and sprinted back to get photos. Field marks when first seen and then later as follows: noticeable white collar and throat making it easy to pick out, very layered face like a beautiful sponge cake, green, black, white, not sure more of the specific field marks but that’s the gist of the bird

Media notes: White collar and large tail spots.
Observation Details: At 5:14 I was walking out of the CE’s and I saw a hummingbird fly over my head and land on a branch. Instantly it caught my attention as unusual.  Field marks are as follows: Its back and crown were a striking emerald green, not the buff-green you see in an ANHU. Additionally, it was rocking some seriously dark and contrasty “mascara” (auriculars) creating a dark masked appearance (likely indicates juvenile male bird). It also had a blazing white throat, collar, and breast with hints of warm buff restricted to the flanks. Described by EM as “layered, like a beautiful sponge cake.” Its bill was short and straight. Its tail, which was held slightly fanned and motionless, had large, copious white spots. An absolutely gorgeous tail shot was acquired by EM (see the seventh photo attached below) showing a perfectly rounded r5 feather! Its tail extended well beyond its wings (see digibins and Oscars photos (https://ebird.org/checklist/S118363194)). Additionally, Oscar got a nice shot the wings showing very sharp p1-p6 feathers. Its gorget area had subtle but beautiful feathers in small lines vertically, recalling an HY bird. One or two dark regions in the gorget were also noted at some angles but never caught the light (also supports HY male theory?).  Black-chinned Hummingbird is the obvious look-a-like species: Primarily eliminated by rounded r5 feather (7th photo below). And small and very sharp p1-p6 feathers (Oscar's clutch ID pic: https://macaulaylibrary.org/asset/482518091).  Secondary ID marks are as follows: This bird had a very unusual and difficult to describe bright green crown, very different from the dusky and dull green crown of a BCHU. This bird's dark auriculars are too dark for a female/immature BCHU. Tail projection was significantly longer than wing tips.  Tertiary field marks: The bird in question had a short bill, but since there is overlap between species it’s not a good identification mark. Additionally, the bird’s wings were slim and razor-like with a relatively dark color. That being said, the light was changing constantly and that should also not be considered a field mark.   This bird had a habit of hunkering down low in the flowers and then spontaneously flying away minutes later. A few times it was chased by the other abundant ANHU. It displayed aggression towards them and even fanned its tail.  Only vocalized once throughout my whole stay, it was in response to the RUHU. Four or five classic "chimp" calls and one faint chase call. See poor audio recording below.  This bird was located in the large Pink Valerian flower patch on the northside of the hill. Exact location here: (37.744127, -122.414295).   Accepted by CBRC (2022-053).  A truly miraculous find!!! A 7th county record and a 1st city. My 5th species of hummingbird for the hill (not including Anna's Hummingbird x Selasphorus sp.) and the #150 species for the hotspot.

Observation Details: A juvenile male Ruby-throated Hummingbird has been visiting the salvia and hummingbird feeders in the yard. It has been here for at least the past 5 days.  The upperparts are concolorous green with some dull faded areas showing. The crown is dullish green but not grayish as in Black-throated Hummingbird The underparts are white with faint cinnamon wash to the sides/flanks. The white neatly spotted/flecked throat contrasts with the dark auricular. The tail is noticeably forked and extends well beyond the primaries. The bill is shortish, shorter than an adult which is consistent with a juvenile. The P10 primary is tapered giving a scabbard appearance not blunt or squared as in BTHU There is no rufous on the bird anywhere eliminating all selasphorus possibilities.

Male and female were fighting over the feeder. The male is typically in charge of the feeder, but this female seemed equally matched. They fought for about 3 minutes, the male diving at the female and the female being mostly defensive. Several times both had to drink from the feeder at the same time out of sheer exhaustion, before resuming the fight. After a while the female had had enough and flew off.

Observation Details: See picture RTHU identified mostly by primary feathers #7,8,9, 10 have pointy tips (rather than U shape as in BCHU) and the tail extends longer than wings. RTHU has been visiting feeder off and on since September/October. I have been discussing humming bird ID with Russ Wigh. Humming birds are present in Savannah during winter and have been visiting feeders located at Diana Churchill’s, Russ Wigh’s, and other properties. Many species including RTHU have been wintering in south eastern United States as stated in Cornell’s Feederwatch program (https://feederwatch.org/blog/ruby-throated-hummingbirds-wintering-northward-at-a-nectar-feeder-near-you/, Cubie, 2014 in The Wilson Journal of Ornithology, 126, 4, (775)., and Kaufman, K., Field Guide to Advanced Birding 2011.  In addition, the Carolina Bird Club has recognized them as widespread during winter https://www.carolinabirdclub.org/misc/hummingbirds/winterhummingbirds.html).

Observation Details: Observer Kate Warrick.  This Ruby-throated Hummingbird, present 24 (here) to 26 August, in the wilds 50 km n. of Beaver Creek, Yukon is astonishing given the extremely remote location, and that anyone would consider putting up a hummingbird feeder there. The narrower inner primaries and wider outer primaries help distinguish it from the very similar Anna's Hummingbird.  ID analysis from Alvaro Jaramillo It’s a Ruby-throated Hummingbird. Apart from the very pale underparts including a white breast band it lacks the densely spotted throat and grayish underparts of Anna’s, it also looks small and slim based on the fake flower size. But key is the primary structure that you can see on that last photo. The inner primaries are narrower, the outers much wider and almost paddle like. This increasing width of primaries is only seen on Archilochus, and the green back and overall tone is good for Ruby-throated, not Black-chinned."

Observation Details: RTHU 4, continues, Images 1, 2 and 8.  New RTHU, I have labelled as RTHU 9,  Images 3 to 7.  A  RTHU 4. Developing gorget, more heavily on the right side. Buffy breast, belly and flanks, with darker area before vent. "Fractured" looking topsides' plumage. Probably a juvenile male.  RTHU 9 first seen and reported on this checklist.  RTHU 9 has a pristine gorget (probably juvenile female) with a light flank tone.  The Images 3 to 5 should show some gorget development with the neck fairly stretched, but shows none, unlike RTHU 4.  Compare to first Image, showing RTHU 4 in a non-stretched neck pose, but still showing gorget flecks, to images 3 to 5 of RTHU 9.  RTHU 9 shows much lighter tone than RTHU 4 on the breast belly and flanks.  Compare flight images of RTHU 9 (Images 6 and 7) with RTHU 4 flight image 9 in similar poses and area, the Salvia, darcyi, by the patio.  RTHU 9 shows none of the plumage "fracturing" on the back that can be seen on RTHU 4.  RTHU 9's wing tips and greenish crown look good for RTHU vs. BCHU.  [RTHU 9 was seen the next morning in the same area, near the patio.]

One juv found by Steve Tucker today. Photos. Defending flowers in left Corymbia tree by small mausoleum as one faces the bay. Early on, before all the cameras were aimed at the tree and were clicking all at once, I did hear the soft, husky 'chimp' or 'tsimp' call-note than recalls Black-chinned. Vis-a-vis that species, this hummer was very bright green above, very bright white below without conspicuous buff on flanks; a very contrasting black 'mask' from around eye through lores; a shorter bill; and a tendency to turn its tail up when foraging but not pump its tail tail (e.g., not tail-wagging) but did spread its tail when hovering. This is the second record for Monterey County. The first was in this same Corymbia tree from 9-12 Sep 2019, but at the time that bird was not identified confidently to species. Sheri Williamson identified that 2019 bird from photos some months later.

Observation Details: Continuing. Stater JF and JW. Maybe 2, certainly one young male. Pics. We watched a female/immature type bird guarding a feeder most of the time we were here but several times before we left, light hit the assumed same bird well and a single gorget feather was notably a vibrant ruby color. Before seeing the ruby feather we observed relatively short straight bill, dark auricular patch below white postocular spot, quite forked tail, buffy flanks, and pointed p10 feather giving the knife like wing shape as opposed to club like BCHU wing shape. Seemingly brighter emerald green upperparts and cleaner white below than typical BCHU. Somewhat out of focus, but one of JW’s pics shows the ruby gorget feather.

A clear archilochus hummingbird with no rufous seen in the tail.  Selasphorus ruled out with tail pattern, and Black-chinned ruled out by the overall bright green coloration on the crown and back, narrower primaries when folded, and relatively shorter bill.  I did not observe frequent tail-pumping as one would expect from BCHU.  This bird only fed while hovering, so that should have been evident.  Calliope ruled out by size, tail being longer than the wings, and lack of brighter buff coloration in the flanks. Anna's ruled out also by the brightness of the bird, especially in the breast and flanks and the call not produced by this bird was right for RTHU and not nearly as emphatic and squeaky like Anna's.

Updated with photos in 2019 from that time/location as original links, below, may be outdated.  Kayaking to the point noted on map (overcast to sunny skies temps in the high 50s/low 60s about 10:45 a.m.), I was trying to locate a singing Prothonotary Warbler when I heard an agitated Ruby-throated Hummingbird chatting above me amongst the tree canopy that was covering my location (about 50 feet from shore in amongst some small trees growing up from within the river). I noticed I had drifted into a territory where there was a fairly low hanging nest (about 12 feet above water level). I backed my kayak out and positioned myself at a safe distance from the nest and behind some other vegetation. For about 30 minutes I observed the Hummingbird flying in and out of the nest area with nesting materials. I only ever saw or heard this lone Hummingbird in the area. This bird arrived 22 September. Nectar feeder was still up as I leave it for 2 weeks after my last sighting; previous sighting was 14 September.  This is not an adult male, there are no subadult male gorget feathers, and I suspect it is an adult female. The white tip of the tail projects beyond the wingtips. The bird shows up to the feeder shortly after dawn when I put it out, comes and goes all day, and stays drinking nectar until dark. It is skittish and zips off anytime I get near the screen door window. It appears puffed up much of the time and the flight pattern is not as strong and direct as typical of an in season Ruby-throat.

3 RTHU Were here from 9/5...F & JM left by 7:30am and the MM left about 8am. The morning started off slow and the pace of hummers passing through peaked between 12:30 - 2:00pm and started to slow down again. Lots of chasing during that period. Although winds were still out of the south, at least they weren't as strong as yesterday...mainly 15-25 mph all day. It is so surprising sometimes that the urge to migrate is so strong, they will buck head winds such as this and stronger like yesterday. Observation Details: At 5:14 I was walking out of the CE’s and I saw a hummingbird fly over my head and land on a branch. Instantly it caught my attention as unusual.  Field marks are as follows: Its back and crown were a striking emerald green, not the buff-green you see in an ANHU. Additionally, it was rocking some seriously dark and contrasty “mascara” (auriculars) creating a dark masked appearance (likely indicates juvenile male bird). It also had a blazing white throat, collar, and breast with hints of warm buff restricted to the flanks. Described by EM as “layered, like a beautiful sponge cake.” Its bill was short and straight. Its tail, which was held slightly fanned and motionless, had large, copious white spots. An absolutely gorgeous tail shot was acquired by EM (see the seventh photo attached below) showing a perfectly rounded r5 feather! Its tail extended well beyond its wings (see digibins and Oscars photos (https://ebird.org/checklist/S118363194)). Additionally, Oscar got a nice shot the wings showing very sharp p1-p6 feathers. Its gorget area had subtle but beautiful feathers in small lines vertically, recalling an HY bird. One or two dark regions in the gorget were also noted at some angles but never caught the light (also supports HY male theory?).  Black-chinned Hummingbird is the obvious look-a-like species: Primarily eliminated by rounded r5 feather (7th photo below). And small and very sharp p1-p6 feathers (Oscar's clutch ID pic: https://macaulaylibrary.org/asset/482518091).  Secondary ID marks are as follows: This bird had a very unusual and difficult to describe bright green crown, very different from the dusky and dull green crown of a BCHU. This bird's dark auriculars are too dark for a female/immature BCHU. Tail projection was significantly longer than wing tips.  Tertiary field marks: The bird in question had a short bill, but since there is overlap between species it’s not a good identification mark. Additionally, the bird’s wings were slim and razor-like with a relatively dark color. That being said, the light was changing constantly and that should also not be considered a field mark.   This bird had a habit of hunkering down low in the flowers and then spontaneously flying away minutes later. A few times it was chased by the other abundant ANHU. It displayed aggression towards them and even fanned its tail.  Only vocalized once throughout my whole stay, it was in response to the RUHU. Four or five classic "chimp" calls and one faint chase call. See poor audio recording below.  This bird was located in the large Pink Valerian flower patch on the northside of the hill. Exact location here: (37.744127, -122.414295).   Accepted by CBRC (2022-053).  A truly miraculous find!!! A 7th county record and a 1st city. My 5th species of hummingbird for the hill (not including Anna's Hummingbird x Selasphorus sp.) and the #150 species for the hotspot.

*****HOLY ARCHILOCHUS!!!!!! Full details to cbrc. Pending acceptance would represent the first record for Mendocino county. Feeding on nosturtiums and alders here: (39.1278001, -123.7157375). Observed from ~8:10-10:12 with approximately half that time the bird was in view, and then again just before 11 as I was passing back upslope. Description: Small, slender hummer in between size of seladphorus and annas. Electric green back, extending from tail all the way to the crown, without any discernible difference between the color of the crown and the color of the back. The underparts contrasted sharply with the bright, pearly whitish underparts, distinctly whiter than the adjancent annas in the same patch. The bird had a pronounced and prominent “mask”. Bold white crescent behind eye. Flanks washed dull green. The throat was overall very clean whitish, with dark spangling up and down the whole length. On a couple of occasions the bird tilted in such a way that a single red gorget feather was visible, though I only saw this three times: once thru bins, and twice in the scope. I was able to photograph the outermost primary to confirm it was narrow-tipped and not blunt-tipped as it would be on a black-chin. The bird called perhaps a dozen times, all typical liquid Archilochus calls, solidly similar to selas and indistinguishable from black-chin to my ear, and totally different from annas. I was unable to get recodings of the call, as it would give it once then stop for minutes

One juv found by Steve Tucker today. Photos. Defending flowers in left Corymbia tree by small mausoleum as one faces the bay. Early on, before all the cameras were aimed at the tree and were clicking all at once, I did hear the soft, husky 'chimp' or 'tsimp' call-note than recalls Black-chinned. Vis-a-vis that species, this hummer was very bright green above, very bright white below without conspicuous buff on flanks; a very contrasting black 'mask' from around eye through lores; a shorter bill; and a tendency to turn its tail up when foraging but not pump its tail tail (e.g., not tail-wagging) but did spread its tail when hovering. This is the second record for Monterey County. The first was in this same Corymbia tree from 9-12 Sep 2019, but at the time that bird was not identified confidently to species. Sheri Williamson identified that 2019 bird from photos some months later.

Visiting feeders for at least 4 days.  Same size as Black-Chinned Hummingbird. Nearly straight, medium-long, dark bill. Black primaries: P1-P5 narrow, P6-P10 broad; P10 narrower than P9, and tapered, unlike Black-Chinned. Deeply forked tail: R1 iridescent green, R2 proximal iridescent green and distal black, R3-R5 as R2 plus white tip. Head, nape, back, and coverts bright iridescent green. Gray-green auriculars and triangular white ear spot.  White throat with minor green spots separated from green-spotted white breast and belly by a flank patch of dull green. White throat extends toward the nape, forming a partial collar. Spots on throat, green flanks, and tapered R5 are compatible with HY male.  Found by N Lethaby. ID help from W Fritz, P Lehman, C Marantz, P Pyle, V Remsen, and Howell, S.N.G. (2001). "Field Identification of Archilochus Hummingbirds". Birders Journal 10: 26-48.

Observation Details: Adult female captured during regular banding operation. Not seen again so not a chaseable bird. Slow to report because the ID was challenging and we needed to consult with experts. Adult (After Hatch Year) age was determined by lack of bill corrugations (even though the bill wasn't entirely smooth) and the amount of feather wear. Female by lack of an iridescent gorget (though one dark feather in throat), but the shape of the outer tail feather is a bit more like a young male, though we were told within the range for adult female. Narrow, pointed shape of p10 (outermost primary) and vibrant green above point to Ruby-throat over Black-chinned (the most similar species). More details will be added.

Observation Details: See picture RTHU identified mostly by primary feathers #7,8,9, 10 have pointy tips (rather than U shape as in BCHU) and the tail extends longer than wings. RTHU has been visiting feeder off and on since September/October. I have been discussing humming bird ID with Russ Wigh. Humming birds are present in Savannah during winter and have been visiting feeders located at Diana Churchill’s, Russ Wigh’s, and other properties. Many species including RTHU have been wintering in south eastern United States as stated in Cornell’s Feederwatch program (https://feederwatch.org/blog/ruby-throated-hummingbirds-wintering-northward-at-a-nectar-feeder-near-you/, Cubie, 2014 in The Wilson Journal of Ornithology, 126, 4, (775)., and Kaufman, K., Field Guide to Advanced Birding 2011.  In addition, the Carolina Bird Club has recognized them as widespread during winter https://www.carolinabirdclub.org/misc/hummingbirds/winterhummingbirds.html).

Media notes: Adult male Ruby-throated Hummingbird found and photographed by Curtis A. Marantz on 10 November 2017 at Lake Tamarisk, Desert Center, Riverside County, California.
Observation Details: This was a notably small bird with a posture that was typical of a hummingbird.  The bill was long, slim, and tubular.  I further noted that the bill was very slightly decurved and just barely longer than the head was wide.  The forehead was sloping and the crown was gently rounded on a head that was unremarkable in size for a hummingbird.  The neck was short and inconspicuous, yet seemingly slimmer than that of an Anna’s Hummingbird.  I also thought this bird was a little slimmer and seemingly smaller than an Anna’s Hummingbird, but I never clearly saw the two species in direct comparison.  The wings were long and sickle-like with the primaries extending well beyond the secondaries in the closed wing and the wingtip having a stair-stepped appearance given the graduated primaries, but I failed to note both the primary projection and the placement of the wingtips relative to the tail.  I noted quite clearly that the tail was short and notched at the tip, with the corners tapering to relatively finely pointed tips, but I did not notice the length of the tail relative to field-marks on the body.  The undertail and uppertail coverts were both relatively long, yet both fell short of even the center of the tail.  The legs were short and the feet were quite small.  I really saw nothing on the spread wings of the flying bird that was all that useful apart from the fact that the wings were beating very rapidly, and that they were relatively long and slim. This was a colorful and well-marked bird.  I never clearly saw the forehead, but the crown, nape, and back and side of the neck were an iridescent, forest-green in color that was both relatively dark and seemingly with a blue component to the green.  The back, scapulars, and rump were also about this same shade of green, as apparently were the wing coverts located near the bird’s shoulder.  I thought the uppertail coverts were about the same color as the rump, but the central rectrices appeared to be slightly darker, albeit with at least some green iridescence.  The outer several pairs of rectrices appeared to be uniformly black from above, but it was also a bit difficult to see the spread tail clearly.  I was never quite sure about the color of the lores, the supraloral region, or the superciliary region, all of which appeared to be quite dark.  I did notice in the field, a small, white spot behind each eye and also that the lower part of the face, from the chin across the submoustachial region, were uniformly black in color.  The gorget often appeared black when seen in less than ideal light, and it was squared off at the corners without the flared “wings” that are typical of Anna’s and especially Costa’s Hummingbirds.  When the light hit the throat just right it glowed with a fire-red color that was both a bit different from the bright pink of the Anna’s Hummingbirds and with the red contrasting sharply with the black of the chin and upper part of the throat.  The lower edge of the gorget was sharply demarcated along a line that extended straight across the demarcation between the throat and upper breast, below which was a broad, and strikingly white collar that extended across the breast and sides.  The flanks were rather broadly about the same shade of forest-green as the upperparts, but the center of the lower breast and belly appeared to be narrowly whitish.  I further noted that the lower part of the belly and the undertail coverts had a somewhat dingy and diffusely mottled appearance, but the underside of the tail appeared to be uniformly dark. The bill was black, the eyes were dark enough as to appear black in the field, and what I could see of the legs and feet when the bird was hovering at the feeder appeared to be at least blackish if not truly black. My impression was that this bird was rather quiet, in that I heard it give only two or three times soft “tschew” calls that were similar to those of Black-chinned Hummingbird (A. alexandri).

The broad outer primaries and narrow inner primaries (note change in width from P7 to P6) indicate an  Archilochus hummingbird. The relatively narrow and tapered P10, along with the notched inner webs of the inner primary tips are indicative of Ruby-throated Hummingbird.  This bird is an immature, as seen by the buff tips of the feathers, especially on the crown and nape.  The almost unmarked throat (with just a few metallic green feathers at the edge), as well as a tiny white tip to R2, point to the bird being a female. The spot. Several times 20+ in view, and 10 more and 10 more ad infinitum, always about 5 if you look around, always birds appearing out of the forest and disappearing back into the forest. Banding shows it's not all the same birds but constant turnover all day. Probably 100 different individuals seen is a more realistic estimate. Previous work suggest that feeding about 2 gallons (1 part sugar 4 parts water) per day, as Jan Reed has been doing lately, means about 1000 hummingbirds/day are passing through her feeding station. This summer she had a recapture of an individual originally banded in 2014. Oldest they've had is 9 years. She's had more birds this year than last year. Last year she fed 163 pounds of sugar. 2018 was 185 lbs. This year will be higher than last year since she's fed many more pounds of sugar this month than same month last year. They have been keeping records since 2000. Her husband John started feeding hummers just putting sugar water in a saucer at this site back in 1969.

Observation Details: Received word from Marshall Iliff via Todd Day that this is a hatch year female Ruby-throated Hummingbird, based on the features visible in the photographs: "it's Archilochus for sure (narrow inner pp) and then clean white throat = HY female). HY female much have get very worn and brown and pale on cheeks AND LORES. This bird rather has typical rthu dark lores, a triangular wedge pointing toward bill base. On much that's a half moon crescent. Also back color matches emerald green of rthu for me and bill length not at all impressive. For me, p10 is obviously narrower than p9 and not particularly broad. On obvious bchu p10 is broad and broader, more club shaped than p9. That's somewhat variable and tough for me at times, but here it supports what I see in face pattern. Imm males and ad females are harder, but imm makes use shoe throat pattern by Nov and ad females have a decent hint of the fave pattern characters above. Aging is critical, but not too hard."  This female hummingbird Initially flew in at 12:32 PM, and I spent the next 71 minutes watching it, mostly perched in a brownish shrub next to where David Clark found the Tropical/Couch's Kingbird last week (specifically here: 36.906766, -76.199237), or zooming around within 50 feet of this site. The bird was very responsive to BCHU calls, pumping its tail while perched & chattering away (voice recordings attached below), but unless I was prompting it with the calls, it was not pumping its tail. Sunlight was hitting right on the side of the shrub the bird spent most of its time perched on, so most of the images are very washed out, but those showing the bird on the nearby wire (holding up parts of the lighting display for the festival of lights the Garden puts on) are truer to the actual color of the bird.

One adult male at the feeder, the first for the "fall" season this year.  (Seems early, but will check against graphs and previous fall occurrences here.)  Having now lived here a bit over three years (here since June 2021), checked past eBird recordings for the first fall arrival dates of RTHU (these all being adult males of course).  Today's bird was the earliest fall arrival compared to the three previous fall seasons, with the others being August 16 (2021), August 12 (2022), and August 20 (2023).  The Travis Audubon's seasonal status bargraphs for "The Birds of Austin TX Region" shows RTHU (beyond the few that summer in the Austin area) beginning to show up just after the first third of August--so today's RTHU fits in well with their expected arrival for the general area.

Observation Details: One small bird photographed coming to feeder, showed 2 ruby gorget feathers, also some rust on flanks, chin?, and above eye. Thick bill misshapen, tail appears long, small white spot behind eye (no other white on face). Gorget molting in, speculation by bird bander (didn't band) and Craig that this is a Calliope. Fred Basset notes "My guess is that bird is a juvenile male Ruby-throated with a bit more buff on its sides than normal. The color in that one iridescent gorget feather pretty much rules out Calliope."

initially considered possible Black-chinned Hummingbird by two experts, but better photos clearly showed RTHU characteristics: uniform green back and crown; straight bill; pointed, not rounded outer primaries; dark auricular and prominent white spot behind eye.  I've observed and photographed numerous BCHU in Arizona. photos

The rufous on this hummingbird had me thinking Rufous Hummingbird. I sent my photos to Allen Chartier, our Michigan hummingbird bander and expert. His comments are “The shapes of the primaries rule out Rufous or Allen's, or Black-chinned. The tail is very worn but has no rufous in it that I can see. Some immature male Ruby-throats have buffy on the flanks and an occasional red throat feather. So I think your bird is a Ruby-throat.” My thanks to Allen.
